Introduction

The first few years of a childâs life are a vital window for laying the foundations of health, learning, and emotional well-being. However, for millions of children around the world, this critical window is one of deprivation, malnutrition, and missed opportunities.

This report uses UNICEFâs global indicators to examine the realities of children across countries â highlighting gaps in stunting, deprivation, and life outcomes. With stark visuals and sharp analysis, we unveil the cycles of injustice that still limit the possibilities of far too many young people.

Every statistic is a tale. Every chart charts a future we can choose to change. It is our shared responsibility to ensure that every child not only survives but actually thrives.

The Invisible Crisis: Child Stunting Around the World

Code 
# Load data
df = indicator_2.copy()
df = df[df['indicator'].str.contains('Stunting', case=False)]
latest = df.sort_values('time_period').groupby('country').tail(1)

# Load Natural Earth shapefile
shapefile = shpreader.natural_earth(resolution='110m', category='cultural', name='admin_0_countries')
reader = shpreader.Reader(shapefile)
countries = list(reader.records())

# Indicator map
indicator_map = dict(zip(latest['country'], latest['obs_value']))
max_value = np.nanmax(list(indicator_map.values()))
min_value = np.nanmin(list(indicator_map.values()))
norm = colors.Normalize(vmin=min_value, vmax=max_value)

# Color map
cmap = cm.Purples

# Setup figure
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(24, 16), subplot_kw={'projection': ccrs.PlateCarree()})
fig.patch.set_facecolor('#E6E6FA')
ax.set_global()

# Background features
ax.add_feature(cfeature.OCEAN, facecolor='#CFE7F3')  #  light ocean blue
ax.add_feature(cfeature.LAND, facecolor='#FAFAFA')   # grey land
ax.coastlines(linewidth=1.2, color='black')
ax.add_feature(cfeature.BORDERS, edgecolor='black', linewidth=1.0)

# Plot countries
for country in countries:
    country_name = country.attributes['NAME_LONG']
    value = indicator_map.get(country_name)
    if value is not None:
        color = cmap(norm(value))
    else:
        color = 'grey'  # very light grey for missing data
    ax.add_geometries(
        [country.geometry],
        crs=ccrs.PlateCarree(),
        facecolor=color,
        edgecolor='black',        # Strong black borders
        linewidth=0.6
    )

# Colorbar
sm = cm.ScalarMappable(cmap=cmap, norm=norm)
sm.set_array([])
cbar = fig.colorbar(sm, ax=ax, orientation='horizontal', pad=0.03, shrink=0.7)
cbar.set_label('Child Stunting (Thousands)', fontsize=18)

# Title
# ax.set_title('Global Child Stunting Rates (Enhanced Borders & Elegant Colors)',
#              fontsize=30, fontweight='bold', pad=30)

plt.show()

The worldwide illustration of child stunting shows major disparities throughout different geographical areas.

  • Regions like Sub-Saharan Africa and South Asia demonstrate the highest instances of child stunting since poverty and food scarcity together with inadequate health facilities block children from normal growth. The nations of India and Pakistan with Nigeria join ranks as global leaders in child stunting since millions of their children are at risk.

  • The stunting situation in Latin America together with Southeast Asian nations demonstrates two different patterns because select nations experience improvement and alternative nations face enduring difficulties.

  • The three geographic regions of Europe along with North America and East Asia display the lowest rates of stunting because they maintain robust healthcare systems combined with nutritious diets and safety programs.

National policies alongside investments into early childhood development together with fair economic growth determine substantial differences between regions as well as within regions.

Every map segment with darker coloring reflects populations that face risk in subsequent generations since prompt intervention would make this difference.

Bar chart: Top 10 Countries with Highest Child deprivations

Code 
# Load data
df = indicator_1.copy()

df_total = df[df['sex'] == 'Total']

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 6))

ax.barh(top10['country'], top10['obs_value'], color='mediumpurple')
ax.set_xlabel('% of Children with Multiple Deprivations')
#ax.set_title('Top 10 Countries with Highest Child Deprivations')
ax.invert_yaxis()  # Highest at top
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

The bar chart presentation of child deprivation reveals multiple disadvantages that children encounter throughout different global areas:

  • Most nations facing severe deprivations for children primarily exist in Sub-Saharan Africa and South Asia.
  • Severe deprivation faces more than half of each child living in Nigeria and Chad and the Central African Republic.
  • From the data it is evident that deprivation extends beyond Africa since Bangladesh and Afghanistan stand near the top rankings.
  • The combination of conflict and poverty and inadequate infrastructure systems therein results in restricted child access to basic rights in these nations.
  • The wide difference between nations demonstrates the essential need for worldwide initiatives that direct resources toward improving child welfare through better life prospects.

Under such conditions children require basic survival instead of development opportunities.

Time series: Child Stunting Trends in selected countries

Code 
#filter for total
indicator_2_total = indicator_2[indicator_2['sex'] == 'Total'].copy()

# Choose a few countries to display
selected_countries = ['India', 'Nigeria', 'Bangladesh', 'Ethiopia', 'Pakistan']

# Filter dataset
subset = indicator_2_total[indicator_2_total['country'].isin(selected_countries)]

# Setup figure
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15,9))
fig.patch.set_facecolor('#E6E6FA')  # lavender
ax.set_facecolor('#f9f9f9')

# Use Set2 color palette
color_palette = plt.get_cmap('Set2')

# Plot each country
for idx, country in enumerate(selected_countries):
    country_data = subset[subset['country'] == country]
    ax.plot(
        country_data['time_period'],
        country_data['obs_value'],
        label=country,
        color=color_palette(idx),  # Use nice distinct soft colors
        linewidth=3,
        marker='o',
        markersize=8,
        markerfacecolor='white',
        markeredgewidth=2
    )

# Titles and labels
# ax.set_title('A Decade of Hope and Struggle: Child Stunting Trends',
#              fontsize=28, fontweight='bold', pad=25)
ax.set_xlabel('Year', fontsize=18, labelpad=15)
ax.set_ylabel('Stunted Children (Thousands)', fontsize=18, labelpad=15)

# Grid
ax.grid(True, linestyle='--', color='white', alpha=0.8)

# Legend
ax.legend(title='Country', fontsize=14, title_fontsize=16, loc='best', frameon=True, facecolor='white', framealpha=0.9)

# Ticks
ax.tick_params(axis='both', which='major', labelsize=14)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

The trend of child stunting history shows improvement and cyclical challenges:

  • Bangladesh shows a steady decline in stunting across the years, which is the impact of sustained investment in nutrition, health, and education interventions.

  • India increases but still has an absolute high because of its large population.

  • Ethiopia and Nigeria have fluctuating trends, demonstrating chronic instability around food insecurity, conflict, and health system limitations.

  • Pakistanâs progress is slower and less consistent, signaling the need for more targeted child development interventions.

  • Despite some positive trends, millions of children in these countries remain stunted, showing that the crisis, though improving, is far from over.

These lines on this graph follow not just data points â but dreams and futures of an entire generation.

Linear Regeression: Stunting Vs Deprivation

Code 
# Filter for 'Total'
indicator_1_total = indicator_1[indicator_1['sex'] == 'Total'].copy()
indicator_2_total = indicator_2[indicator_2['sex'] == 'Total'].copy()

# Latest year for each country
indicator_1_latest = indicator_1_total.sort_values('time_period').groupby('country').tail(1)
indicator_2_latest = indicator_2_total.sort_values('time_period').groupby('country').tail(1)

# Merge on country
merged = pd.merge(indicator_1_latest, indicator_2_latest, on='country', suffixes=('_deprivation', '_stunting'))

# Prepare X and Y
x = merged['obs_value_deprivation']
y = merged['obs_value_stunting']

# Clean NaNs
mask = (~x.isna()) & (~y.isna())
x = x[mask]
y = y[mask]

# Create figure
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(14, 9))
fig.patch.set_facecolor('#E6E6FA')  # light lavender
ax.set_facecolor('#F9F9F9')         # Very light inside plot

# Scatter points
scatter = ax.scatter(
    x, y,
    c=y, cmap='plasma',   # Beautiful vibrant plasma colors
    s=100, alpha=0.8, edgecolor='white', linewidth=0.5
)

# Add colorbar
cbar = plt.colorbar(scatter, ax=ax, shrink=0.8, pad=0.02)
cbar.set_label('Child Stunting (Thousands)', fontsize=13)

# Linear regression
slope, intercept, r_value, p_value, std_err = linregress(x, y)
x_vals = np.linspace(x.min(), x.max(), 300)
y_vals = intercept + slope * x_vals

# Plot regression line
ax.plot(
    x_vals, y_vals,
    color='deepskyblue',
    linewidth=4, linestyle='-',
    label=f'Regression Line y = {slope:.2f}*x + {intercept:.2f}'
)

# Titles and labels
# ax.set_title('When Deprivation Leads to Stunting: A Global Snapshot',
#              fontsize=26, fontweight='bold', pad=30, loc='center')
ax.set_xlabel('% of Children with Multiple Deprivations', fontsize=18, labelpad=12)
ax.set_ylabel('Child Stunting (Thousands)', fontsize=18, labelpad=12)

# Style
ax.legend(fontsize=14)
ax.grid(True, linestyle='--', color='white', alpha=0.7)
ax.tick_params(axis='both', which='major', labelsize=13)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

The regression plot draws a grim and ominous line between child deprivation and life expectancy:

  • More children suffering from multiple deprivations in a nation are associated with lower life expectancy.

  • The declining trend of the regression line reaffirms that deprivation during early childhood affects long-term survival and health status at the national level.

  • High-deprivation countries suffer not only short-term child health issues, but also long-term population health challenges.

The connection is not absolute, but the trend is certain.opportunities in childhood are limited, lives are shorter and less secure. Fighting child deprivation is not an act of charity â it is an investment in a healthier, more resilient world.

When childhoods are poor, entire nations lose decades of promise.

Conclusion

The figures in this report paint a harsh and urgent picture: millions of kids all over the world remain denied their basic rights of health, nutrition, and possibility.

Glimmers of hopeful change in some regions exist side by side with stubborn disparities between countries and within countries that highlight how much there is yet to be done. Stunting, malnourishment, and lower life expectancy are not realities â they are outcomes of choices, policies, and investments.

Each child deserves more than subsistence. Each child deserves an equal chance to grow, learn, and thrive.

The time to act is now:

By equal policies, better health systems, investment in early childhood, and global commitment, we can rechart these pathways â and change the future for millions.
